\begin_layout Chapter
Nucleon Spin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As known from QCD, the nucleon is consisted of the quarks and gluons.
 The total nucleon spin can be expressed as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jaffe1990509"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{Z}^{N}=\frac{1}{2}=(\frac{1}{2}\Delta\Sigma+L_{q})+(\Delta G+L_{g}).\label{eq:spindecom}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The spin of the nucleon is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It includes the quark and gluon angular momentum contributions: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g}$
\end_inset

 respectively, and the intrinsic quark and gluon spin contribution: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\Delta\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The format of the relationship wasn't like this before the QCD corrected
 the quark-parton model.
 The naive quark-parton model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.23.1415"

\end_inset

 was invented long before the QCD in order to describe the nucleon structures.
 Later on the spin crisis between the experiment and the prediction from
 the naive quark-parton model activated the enthusiasm for the study of
 the nucleon spin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Naive Quark-Parton Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spin structure in the naive quark-parton model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When proton is considered to be comprised by only the valence 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 quarks, a simple non-relativistic wave function for proton can be expressed
 as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Filippone:2001ux"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|p\uparrow>=\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}(2|u\uparrow u\uparrow d\downarrow>-|u\uparrow u\downarrow d\uparrow>-|u\downarrow u\uparrow d\uparrow>),\label{eq:protonwave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\uparrow,\downarrow$
\end_inset

 indicate the spin of the quarks or the anti-quarks are parallel or anti-paralle
l to the spin of the proton, respectively.
 The color indices and permutations were suppressed in the equation.
 The contribution of the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 quark can be determined by using the following matrix element and projection
 operator:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u^{\uparrow} & =<p^{\uparrow}|\hat{O_{u\uparrow}}|p^{\uparrow}>,\\
\hat{O_{u\uparrow}} & =\frac{1}{4}(1+\hat{\tau}_{3})(1+\hat{\sigma}_{3}),
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the matrix element gives the number of the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 quark which polarized along the polarization of proton.
 Similar expression can be taken for the 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 quark.
 The quark spin contributions can be defined using the matrix elements above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta u & =u^{\uparrow}-u^{\downarrow},\\
\Delta d & =d^{\uparrow}-d^{\downarrow},
\end{align}

\end_inset

so that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta u & =\frac{1}{2}(<\sigma_{3}>+<\sigma_{3}\tau_{3}>)=\frac{4}{3},\\
\Delta d & =\frac{1}{2}(<\sigma_{3}>-<\sigma_{3}\tau_{3}>)=-\frac{1}{3}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The proton's spin can then be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{Z}^{N}=\frac{1}{2}\Delta\varSigma=\frac{1}{2}(\Delta u+\Delta d+\Delta s)=\frac{1}{2}<\sigma_{3}>=\frac{1}{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which indicates all of the nucleon spin is carried by the quarks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Structure functions in the naive quark-parton model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quark-parton was considered as a mass-less and point-like particle which
 interact electromagnetically like lepton in the naive model.
 The spin-averaged structure functions of hadron, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

, are presented in the naive quark-parton model (QPM) as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F_{1}(x) & =\frac{1}{2}\underset{i}{\sum}e_{i}^{2}[q_{i}(x)+\bar{q}_{i}(x)],\label{eq:nativeQPMF1}\\
F_{2}(x) & =\underset{i}{\sum}e_{i}^{2}x[q_{i}(x)+\bar{q}_{i}(x)],\label{eq:nativeQPMF2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the number density of the quarks and anti-quarks, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the charge of the quark, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the momentum fraction of the nucleon's total momentum carried by a quark
 or anti-quark in the parton model.
 The equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nativeQPMF1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nativeQPMF2"

\end_inset

) lead to Callan-Gross relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.21.311"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{2}(x)=2xF_{1}(x).\label{eq:F2eq2xF1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the polarized scattering the results become more interesting by the
 spin contribution.
 Spin plays an essential role for the more detailed structure of the nucleon.
 The longitudinal spin-dependent structure function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is presented in the naive QPM as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(x)=\frac{1}{2}\underset{i}{\sum}e_{i}^{2}\Delta q_{i}(x),\label{eq:g1native}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the difference of the number density of the quarks (anti-quarks) when
 the helicity parallel and anti-parallel to the nucleon spin, represented
 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta q_{i}(x)=q_{i}^{+}(x)+\bar{q}_{i}^{+}(x)-q_{i}^{-}(x)-\bar{q}_{i}^{-}(x).\label{eq:deltaqi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the helicity is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h=\frac{\vec{\sigma}\cdot\vec{p}}{|\vec{p}|},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 is the particle's momentum, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the Pauli spin matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 structure function represents the charge-weighted quark helicity distributions
 at the Bjorken limit.
 Another spin-dependent structure function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot be leaded to simple results by using the naive quark-parton model
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Anselmino:1994gn"

\end_inset

 and will discussed later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the naive quark-parton model and Ellis-Jaffe sum rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the integration of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 For proton it is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{1}^{p}(x)=\int_{0}^{1}g_{1}(x)dx.\label{eq:eta1p-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1native"

\end_inset

) can be rewritten in terms of linear combinations of quark densities under
 the group of flavor transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(3)_{F}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta q_{3} & =\Delta u-\Delta d,\\
\Delta q_{8} & =\Delta u+\Delta d-2\Delta s,\\
\Delta\Sigma & =\Delta u+\Delta d+\Delta s,
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q_{3}$
\end_inset

 is the third component of an isotopic spin triplet, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q_{8}$
\end_inset

 is the eighth component of an 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(3)_{F}$
\end_inset

 octet, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a flavor singlet.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 becomes as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(x)=\frac{1}{9}[\frac{3}{4}\Delta q_{3}(x)+\frac{1}{4}\Delta q_{8}(x)+\Delta\Sigma(x)].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first moment for the proton is then expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{1}^{p}(x)=\int_{0}^{1}g_{1}(x)dx=\frac{1}{9}(\frac{3}{4}a_{3}+\frac{1}{4}a_{8}+a_{0}),\label{eq:eta1p}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{8}$
\end_inset

 are three weak axial-vector couplings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.9.1444"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a_{0} & =\Delta\sum\equiv\int_{0}^{1}\Delta\Sigma(x)dx,\label{eq:a0}\\
a_{3} & =\int_{0}^{1}\Delta q_{3}(x)dx=\left|\frac{g_{A}}{g_{V}}\right|=F+D,\label{eq:a3}\\
a_{8} & =\int_{0}^{1}\Delta q_{8}(x)dx=3F-D,\label{eq:a8}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 are the symmetric and antisymmetric weak 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(3)_{F}$
\end_inset

 couplings, which assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(3)_{F}$
\end_inset

 is symmetry.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{V}$
\end_inset

 are the axial and vector weak coupling constants of neutron 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-decay$
\end_inset

.
 When assuming the strange (sea) quark in the nucleon is not polarized,
 the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:a0"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:a8"

\end_inset

) leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=a_{8}$
\end_inset

, and the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\varGamma_{1}^{p}(x) & =\frac{1}{12}(F+D)+\frac{5}{36}(3F-D)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{12}\left|\frac{g_{A}}{g_{V}}\right|(1+\frac{5}{3}\frac{3(F/D)-1}{(F/D)+1}),\label{eq:elsumrule}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is the Ellis-Jaffe sum rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.9.1444"

\end_inset

.
 The ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $F/D$
\end_inset

 can be measured from hyperon decays, and implying that: 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=a_{8}\approx0.59$
\end_inset

.
 The result of the first moment can be obtained 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.9.1444"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{1}^{p}(x)=0.186\pm0.004.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Also the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the spin from all of the quarks from the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:a0"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{0}=2S_{z}^{quarks},\label{eq:a0sz}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{z}^{quarks}$
\end_inset

 is the spin combining of all flavor quarks\SpecialChar \@.
 In the naive quark-parton model
 all quarks move parallel to the parent hadron, thus there is no orbital
 angular momentum contributed to the 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{z}$
\end_inset

 carried by the quarks.
 The total spin is expected as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "leadernewcleonspin"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{z}^{quark}=J_{z}=\frac{1}{2}.\label{eq:szquark}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1988 the European Muon Collaboration (EMC) published their final results
 from their study of deep inelastic muon-proton scattering experiment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ashman1988364"

\end_inset

 , the value implied that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}g_{1}(x)dx=0.114\pm0.012\pm0.026,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{z}^{quark}=0.006\pm0.058\pm0.117,\label{eq:EMCresult}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which indicating that the quark spins carry only a little part of the proton
 spin, and the Ellis-Jaffe sum rule in the naive quark-parton model is invalid.
 The large disagreement with the naive quark-parton model result, which
 terms the spin crisis in the parton model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "raeycrisis"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The quark-parton model corrected by QCD
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spin crisis was believed to be resolved by considering a large contribution
 of the polarized gluon.
 Once the QCD theory is accepted as a valid theory for the strong interaction,
 it is introduced to the naive quark-parton model to complement the gluon
 distribution, which describes the strong force between the quarks.
 After introducing the gluon vector potential, it is much more complicated
 to describe the nucleon structure.
 The operator product expansion (OPE) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRev.179.1499"

\end_inset

 is a fundamental understanding originally within QCD that provide the QCD
 prediction for the moments of the structure functions via the sum rules.
 The OPE expresses the product of the two operators in the small distance
 limit 
\begin_inset Formula $d\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{d\rightarrow0}{lim}\sigma_{a}(d)\sigma_{b}(0)=\underset{k}{\Sigma}C_{abk}(d)\sigma_{k}(0),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{abk}$
\end_inset

 are the Wilson coefficients, which are calculable perturbatively in QCD.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset

 are quark and gluon operators of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and spin 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, which are not calculable in perturbative QCD.
 The twist is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\equiv d-n$
\end_inset

.
 The contribution of any operator, i.e., the differential cross section, is
 of order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{-n}(\frac{M}{Q})^{\tau-2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\sqrt{Q^{2}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the squared four-momentum transfer, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}=-q^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

