 The interaction is splitted to two part: The hard interaction (top 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blob
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and the non-perturbative soft interaction (down 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blob
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Unfortunately even if for the simplest QCD correction terms, a vertex correctio
n and a gluon radiative correction are infinite because of the masslessness
 of the quarks.
 The solution is referring to a factorization scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{2}$
\end_inset

, and splitting the interaction terms of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}ln\frac{Q^{2}}{m_{q}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 into two parts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha_{s}ln\frac{Q^{2}}{m_{q}^{2}}=\alpha_{s}ln\frac{Q^{2}}{\mu^{2}}+\alpha_{s}ln\frac{\mu^{2}}{m_{q}^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the strong coupling constant.
 The first term 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}ln\frac{Q^{2}}{\mu^{2}}$
\end_inset

 was absorbed into the hard part, which can be dealt with the perturbative
 QCD.
 The second term 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}ln\frac{\mu^{2}}{m_{q}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 was absorbed into the soft part, which cannot be calculated and need to
 be parametrized.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary number that we can take a choice.
 One optimal choice is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{2}=Q^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The quark-parton densities which are only depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the naive quark-parton model are now depend on both 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

, which break the Bjorken scaling.
 The main effect for the QCD correction is that it introduces a calculable
 logarithmic relation with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 for quark-parton densities, and generates the gluon contribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At present there are three different factorization schemes in use for handling
 the quark-gluon interactions and the gluon contributions to nucleon spin,
 which are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{MS}$
\end_inset

 scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.54.2023"

\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ball1996255"

\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $JET$
\end_inset

 scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carlitz1988"

\end_inset

.
 If considering all orders in perturbation theory there is no difference
 to choose the scheme, but it becomes important when working to leading
 order (LO), next to leading order (NLO), and NNLO.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 scheme and the 
\begin_inset Formula $JET$
\end_inset

 scheme, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be implied as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{0}=\Delta\sum+a_{0}^{gluon},\label{eq:a0QCD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is the quark spin contribution, which is independent with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}^{gluon}$
\end_inset

 is the gluon contribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carlitz1988"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{0}^{gluon}=-3\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{2\pi}\Delta G(Q^{2}),\label{eq:a0gluon}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the run coupling constant in the QCD, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G(Q^{2})\equiv\intop_{0}^{1}dx\Delta G(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

, and parameter 3 correspond to three flavor quarks: 
\begin_inset Formula $u,\ d,\ s$
\end_inset

.
 The equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:a0QCD"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:a0gluon"

\end_inset

) show that the small measured 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 does not imply the small 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The gluon's contribution to the first moment is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{1}^{gluon}(Q^{2})=-3\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{2\pi}\Delta G(Q^{2}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{MS}$
\end_inset

 scheme, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is not the pure quark spin contribution anymore, which includes the interaction
 of quark-gluon.
 In the NLO of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{MS}$
\end_inset

 scheme, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 became to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{0}(Q^{2})=\Delta\Sigma(Q^{2}).\label{eq:a0MS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first moment for proton in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eta1p"

\end_inset

) is corrected as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Larin1994192,yeprogressphys"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{1}^{p}(Q^{2})=\int_{0}^{1}g_{1}(x)dx=(\frac{1}{12}a_{3}+\frac{1}{36}a_{8})C_{ns}(Q^{2})+\frac{1}{9}a_{0}C_{s}(Q^{2}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{MS}$
\end_inset

 scheme, the non-singlet coefficient function 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ns}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 was calculated in the
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}^{3}$
\end_inset

 approximation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{ns}=1-\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi}-3.58(\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})^{2}-20.2153(\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})^{3}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The singlet part 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{9}a_{0}C_{s}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 exists in two forms, one yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 dependent 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.58.112003"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{9}a_{0}C_{s}(Q^{2})=\frac{1}{9}a_{0}(Q^{2})[1-\frac{a_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi}-1.10(\frac{a_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})^{2}],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

another one yields the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}^{inv}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Larin1994192"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{9}a_{0}C_{s}(Q^{2}) & =\frac{1}{9}C_{s}^{inv}(Q^{2})a_{0}^{inv}\nonumber \\
= & \frac{1}{9}[1-0.3333(\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})-0.5495(\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})^{2}+O(\alpha_{s}^{3})]a_{0}^{inv},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}^{inv}$
\end_inset

 is the asymtotic high 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chiral Perturbation Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 region with low energy interactions, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 becomes large, the QCD becomes highly non-perturbative.
 The strong force in the nucleon is relatively strong in the resonance region,
 the quarks and the gluons cannot be escaped to become the free particles.
 The QCD cannot be easily solved in this region, the usual perturbative
 expansion does not work.
 It is better to deal the composite hadrons as the degrees of freedom than
 directly deal with the quarks and gluons in QCD, which called Chiral Perturbati
on Theory (
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bernard200882"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the complete QCD Lagrangian 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bernard:1995dp"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}_{QCD} & =-\frac{1}{4g^{2}}G_{\mu\nu}^{a}G^{\mu\nu,a}+\bar{q}i\gamma^{\mu}D_{\mu}q-\bar{q}\mathcal{M}q,
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the strength of the gluon field, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the quark spinor, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=diag(m_{u},m_{d},m_{s},...)$
\end_inset

 is the quark mass matrix.
 The masses of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 are small compared with the proton's mass, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{u}/m_{e}\approx0.006$
\end_inset

.
 If the quark mass is set to 0, the left and right handed quarks are defined
 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{R,L}=\frac{1}{2}(1\pm\gamma_{5})q,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the chirality is identical to helicity 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 for a massless fermion.
 The main idea of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 is that the left and right handed quarks do not interact each other so
 that the theory admits the 
\begin_inset Formula $U(3)_{L}\times U(3)_{R}$
\end_inset

 symmetry.
 The existed small quark mass breaks the symmetry.
 In the low energy, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 splits the Lagrangian into two parts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{QCD}=\mathcal{L}_{QCD}^{0}+\mathcal{L}_{QCD}^{\mathcal{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{QCD}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the chiral symmetric part, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{QCD}^{\mathcal{0}}=-\bar{q}\mathcal{M}q$
\end_inset

 is regarded as a perturbation to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{QCD}^{0}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The low-energy expansion in small momenta and quark masses involves pion
 loops of the effective theory.
 In the presence of baryons, it becomes more complex since the baryon mass
 is non-vanishing in the chiral limit.
 Two main approaches were considered for dealing of it: heavy baryon 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $HB\chi PT$
\end_inset

) and relativistic baryon 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $RB\chi PT$
\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $HB\chi PT$
\end_inset

 considers the baryons as very heavy and the theory is expanded in inverse
 powers of the baryon mass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.48.3062"

\end_inset

, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $RB\chi PT$
\end_inset

 performs the calculation in a fully relativistic treatment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bernard2002105"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 is available as high as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}=0.2\ GeV^{2}$
\end_inset

, the calculation of it became very productive over the past 15 years.
 The applicability range of it should be resolved by the benchmark tests
 of measurements of the quantities calculable in 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sum rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first moment of the spin structure function is important since it can
 extract the quark spin distribution to the nucleon spin.
 Peoples built several sum rules to study QCD by involving the spin structure
 of the nucleon.
 Including the Ellis-Jaffe sum rule discussed above, there are several sum
 rules related to the first moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we discuss the Bjorken sum rule and the Gerasimov-Drell-Hearn (GDH)
 sum rule for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The Burkhardt-Cottingham sum rule for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 will be discussed in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Bjorken sum rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most fundamental of the definite prediction for the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 dependence of spin-dependent structure functions is the Bjorken sum rule,
 which was derived from light cone current algebra and isospin invariance
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRev.179.1547"

\end_inset

.
 In the naive quark-parton model it has the form of :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{1}^{p}-\Gamma_{1}^{n}=\int_{0}^{1}[g_{1}^{p}(x)-g_{1}^{n}(x)]dx=\frac{1}{6}\left|\frac{g_{A}}{g_{V}}\right|,\label{eq:Bjsumrule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the difference between the first moment of proton and neutron.
 For the finite 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 range, it is corrected by the QCD radiative corrections:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{1}^{p}-\Gamma_{1}^{n}=\frac{1}{6}\left|\frac{g_{A}}{g_{V}}\right|[1-\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi}-3.25(\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})^{2}-13.8(\frac{\alpha_{s}(Q^{2})}{\pi})^{3}+...].\label{eq:BjsumruleQCD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is clear from equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BjsumruleQCD"

\end_inset

) that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 is independent with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{s}$
\end_inset

 becomes to 0, which is the case at 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, otherwise, the bjorken scaling breaks down when the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 are in the region of finite values.
 The Bjorken sum rule is one of the sum rule which the right hand side is
 accurately known.
 Measuring the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}^{p}-\Gamma_{1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at different 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 provides a sensitive test for the QCD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many experiments from SLAC, HERMES, and JLab supported the result of the
 Bjorken sum rule.
 The sum rule is rigorous with only the assumption of isospin invariance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Gerasimov-Drell-Hearn sum rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bjorken sum rule describes the region of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, while the GDH sum rule describes the region of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 With the assumptions of Lorentz and gauge invariance, unitarity and causality,
 the GDH sum rule is derived from the calculation of the forward Compton
 amplitude for real photon scattering from a nucleon 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VincentAnthonySulkosky07"

\end_inset

.
 The GDH sum rule relates to the particle's static properties from the ground
 state to all of its excited states.
 It relates to an energy-weighted integral over its photoabsorption cross
 section to an anomalous magnetic moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.16.908"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I(0)=\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\nu}{\nu}[\sigma_{1/2}(\nu)-\sigma_{3/2}(\nu)]=-2\pi^{2}\alpha\frac{\kappa^{2}}{M^{2}},\label{eq:GDHsumrule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the threshold energy for pion production: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}=m_{\pi}(1+\frac{m_{\pi}}{2M})\approx150\ MeV$
\end_inset

, which ignored the elastic scattering below 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the right hand side of the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GDHsumrule"

\end_inset

) is given by the nucleon's ground state properties that are known exactly,
 the sum rule provides an ideal study for the nucleon's internal structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original GDH sum rule pertains strictly to the real photon case for
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 it is useful to generalize the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

GDH integral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I(Q^{2}) & =\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\nu}{\nu}(1-x)[\sigma_{1/2}(\nu,Q^{2})-\sigma_{3/2}(\nu,Q^{2})]\nonumber \\
 & =2\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\nu}{\nu}(1-x)\sigma'_{TT},\label{eq:GDHintegral}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is valid in all 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 range, where we can connect it with the Bjorken sum rule.
 Study of the connection of these two sum rules can help us to understand
 the transition from the resonance region to the DIS region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Near 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}=0$
\end_inset

, several calculation have been performed using chiral perturbation theory.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

, OPE technology is used to predict.
 The GDH sum rule is not investigated until this century at Mainz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.87.022003"

\end_inset

.
 After that several experiments at Jefferson Lab tried to extract the GDH
 integral 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.89.242301,E97110proposal,E03006eg4-proposal"

\end_inset

.
 Now the data below 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}<0.2\ GeV^{2}$
\end_inset

 is still lacking, which is necessary to extend the integration to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The data from E97-110 and E03-006 at Jeffereson Lab hopefully can extend
 the GDH integral at low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 and test predictions of chiral perturbation theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 Structure Function and the Spin Polarizabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no definition for the structure function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the naive quark-parton model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Anselmino:1994gn"

\end_inset

.
  The later progress shows that it is related to the higher-twist quark-gluon
 correlations and needed to be fixed by using QCD.
 The first reliable result is decomposed by the Wandzura-Wilczek relation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wandzura1977195"

\end_inset

, which is known as the leading twist-2 term of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

, depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{2}^{WW}(x,Q^{2})=-g_{1}(x,Q^{2})+\intop_{x}^{1}\frac{g_{1}(y,Q^{2})}{y}dy.\label{eq:g2WW}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the help of the operator product expansion (OPE) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shuryak1982141,Ji1993217,Stein1995107"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be expanded into leading (twist-2) and higher-twist components if ignoring
 quark mass effect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{2}(x,Q^{2})=g_{2}^{WW}(x,Q^{2})+\bar{g_{2}}(x,Q^{2}),\label{eq:g2expand}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the higher twist part 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{g_{2}}(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{g_{2}}(x,Q^{2})=-\intop_{x}^{1}\frac{\partial}{\partial y}[\frac{m_{q}}{M}h_{T}(y,Q^{2})+\zeta(y,Q^{2})]\frac{dy}{y},\label{eq:g2highertwist}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{q}$
\end_inset

 is the quark mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{T}(y,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 is from the quark transverse polarization distribution which suppressed
 in DIS by 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{q}/M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 is the twist-3 part which from quark-gluon interactions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a good approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 for equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g2WW"

\end_inset

) while the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In the low 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 exhibits large deviations from leading twist behavior.
 While the higher twist is more sensitive to the quark-gluon interaction,
 the study of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 provides a good test for the quark-gluon interaction, especially for the
 study of the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}^{WW}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The generalized forward spin polarizability 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 and The longitudinal-transverse polarizability 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{LT}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming an appropriate high-energy behavior, the spin-flip forward doubly-virtu
al Compton scattering (VVCS) amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{TT}$
\end_inset

 satisfies an unsubtracted dispersion relation as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jpsumrulspin2005,Drechsel200399"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Re[g_{TT}(\nu,Q^{2})-g_{TT}^{pole}(\nu,Q^{2})] & =\frac{\nu}{2\pi^{2}}\mathcal{P}\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{K(\nu',Q^{2})\sigma_{TT}(\nu',Q^{2})}{\nu'^{2}-\nu^{2}}d\nu'\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{2\alpha}{M^{2}}I_{A}(Q^{2})\nu+\gamma_{0}(Q^{2})\nu^{3}+\mathcal{O}(\nu^{5}),\label{eq:gttgttpole}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{TT}^{pole}$
\end_inset

 is the nucleon pole (elastic) contribution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 denotes the principle value integral.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{A}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\nu)$
\end_inset

 term of the Compton amplitude, it can be expressed as the GDH integral
 by expanding a Taylor series 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drechsel200399"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I_{A}(Q^{2}) & =\frac{M^{2}}{4\pi{}^{2}\alpha}\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{K(\nu,Q^{2})}{\nu}\frac{\sigma_{TT}(\nu,Q^{2})}{\nu}d\nu\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{2M^{2}}{Q^{2}}\intop_{0}^{x_{0}}\{g_{1}(x,Q^{2})-\frac{4M^{2}}{Q^{2}}x^{2}g_{2}(x,Q^{2})\}dx.\label{eq:ITT}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\nu^{3})$
\end_inset

 term yields a generalization of the forward spin polarizability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drechsel200399"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\gamma_{0}(Q^{2}) & =(\frac{1}{2\pi^{2}})\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{K(\nu,Q^{2})}{\nu}\frac{\sigma_{TT}(\nu,Q^{2})}{\nu^{3}}d\nu\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{16\alpha M^{2}}{Q^{6}}\intop_{0}^{x_{0}}\{g_{1}(x,Q^{2})-\frac{4M^{2}}{Q^{2}}x^{2}g_{2}(x,Q^{2})\}x^{2}dx.\label{eq:gammaTT}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a similar way with 
\begin_inset Formula $I(0)$
\end_inset

 expressed as the photoabsorption cross section in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GDHsumrule"

\end_inset

), the forward spin polarizability 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{0}=\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}}\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{d\nu}{\nu^{3}}[\sigma_{1/2}(\nu)-\sigma_{3/2}(\nu)].\label{eq:gamma0vc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The longitudinal-transverse interference amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{LT}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed by using the same assumption:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Re[g_{LT}(\nu,Q^{2})-g_{LT}^{pole}(\nu,Q^{2})]=\frac{2\alpha}{M^{2}}QI_{3}(Q^{2})+Q\delta_{LT}(Q^{2})\nu^{2}+\mathcal{O}(\nu^{4}),\label{eq:gLTgLTpole}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(1)$
\end_inset

 term yields an integral by using a similar procedure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I_{3}(Q^{2}) & =\frac{M^{2}}{4\pi\alpha^{2}}\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{K(\nu,Q^{2})}{\nu}\frac{\sigma_{LT}(\nu,Q^{2})}{Q}d\nu\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{2M^{2}}{Q^{2}}\intop_{0}^{x_{0}}\{g_{1}(x,Q^{2})-g_{2}(x,Q^{2})\}x^{2}dx,\label{eq:ILT}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\nu^{2})$
\end_inset

 term yields a generalized longitudinal-transverse polarizability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drechsel200399"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\delta_{LT}(Q^{2}) & =(\frac{1}{2\pi^{2}})\intop_{\nu_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{K(\nu,Q^{2})}{\nu}\frac{\sigma_{LT}(\nu,Q^{2})}{Q\nu^{2}}d\nu\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{16\alpha M^{2}}{Q^{6}}\intop_{0}^{x_{0}}\{g_{1}(x,Q^{2})+g_{2}(x,Q^{2})\}x^{2}dx.\label{eq:deltaLT}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At large 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, the unmeasured region enlarges the uncertainty for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi PT$
\end_inset

 calculation.
 The extra 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\nu^{2}}$
\end_inset

 weighting for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{LT}$
\end_inset

 in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gammaTT"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deltaLT"

\end_inset

) compared with the first moment leads the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 converge quickly in the large-
