\begin_layout Subsection
The Burkhardt-Cottingham Sum Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spin-flip amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{TT}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{LT}$
\end_inset

 are also related to the covariant spin-dependent VVCS amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

, as expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
S_{1}(\nu,Q^{2}) & =\frac{\nu M}{\nu^{2}+Q^{2}}[g_{TT}(\nu,Q^{2})+\frac{Q}{\nu}g_{LT}(\nu,Q^{2})],\label{eq:S1}\\
S_{2}(\nu,Q^{2}) & =-\frac{M^{2}}{\nu^{2}+Q^{2}}[g_{TT}(\nu,Q^{2})-\frac{\nu}{Q}g_{LT}(\nu,Q^{2})].\label{eq:S2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 the unsubtracted dispersion with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu S_{2}$
\end_inset

 lead to the Burkhardt-Cottingham (B-C) sum rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Burkhardt1970453"

\end_inset

 which is valid for any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\intop_{0}^{1}g_{2}(x,Q^{2})=0.\label{eq:BC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The test of the B-C sum rule can be taken either at DIS region or at low
 region.
 The validity of the B-C sum rule depends on the integral at low 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It will be failed if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 exhibits non-Regge behavior at low x 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Soffer2002323"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Higher twist moments 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The moments 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}$
\end_inset

is expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d_{2}(Q^{2}) & =\intop_{0}^{1}x^{2}[2g_{1}(x,Q^{2})+3g_{2}(x,Q^{2})]dx\nonumber \\
 & =3\intop_{0}^{1}x^{2}[g_{2}(x,Q^{2})-g_{2}^{WW}(x,Q^{2})]dx.\label{eq:d2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At large 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

, the higher twist moments 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}$
\end_inset

 is related to the color polarizability, which describes color electric
 and magnetic polarizabilities.
 It can be calculated from Lattice QCD at high 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

, which provides a benchmark test for the Lattice QCD.
 At lower 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

, it provides the study of the transition from perturbative to non-perturbative
 region.
 Since it is the 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 moment of the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}^{WW}$
\end_inset

, it represents a measure of QCD complexity.
\end_layout

